{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.26,0.04,0.19,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"9936"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute tubular necrosis occurs when the kidneys experience a period of reduced blood flow, leading to tissue damage. The immune system responds to this injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following immune responses is most prominent in acute tubular necrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complement activation","T lymphocyte infiltration","B lymphocyte proliferation","Antibody deposition","Natural killer cell recruitment"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute tubular necrosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplement activation\u003C/strong\u003E is a key early event that occurs as part of the innate immune response. The complement cascade, particularly C3a and C5a, contributes to inflammation and tissue injury within minutes to hours of the ischaemic insult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET lymphocyte infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E - Adaptive immune responses involving T cells take days to develop and are not a major feature of acute tubular necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB lymphocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - B cell responses are part of adaptive immunity and not significantly involved in acute tubular necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody deposition\u003C/strong\u003E - Antibody production is an adaptive immune response that takes too long to develop to be relevant in acute injury\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatural killer cell recruitment\u003C/strong\u003E - While NK cells are part of innate immunity, they do not play a major role in acute tubular necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe immune response in acute tubular necrosis is primarily driven by innate immunity, including complement proteins, neutrophils, and inflammatory mediators.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute tubular necrosis primarily activates innate immune responses including complement cascade activation","Complement proteins C3a and C5a contribute to inflammation and tissue injury in acute tubular necrosis","Adaptive immune responses like T cells and antibodies are not major features of acute tubular necrosis"],"references":["Zheng L, Gao W, Hu C, Yang C, Rong R. Immune Cells in Ischemic Acute Kidney Injury. Curr Protein Pept Sci. 2019;20(8):770-776. doi: 10.2174/1389203720666190507102529. PMID: 31060484.","Wen Y, Yang C, Menez SP, Rosenberg AZ, Parikh CR. A Systematic Review of Clinical Characteristics and Histologic Descriptions of Acute Tubular Injury. Kidney Int Rep. 2020 Aug 31;5(11):1993-2001. doi: 10.1016/j.ekir.2020.08.026. PMID: 33163720; PMCID: PMC7609907","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:21:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:23:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7740"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"dat